#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:8
msgid "SYNOPSIS: Setting up Mutt and/or Vim to use Aspell."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:11
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: With this hint you can configure Vim to spell check your "
"documents and emails or you can set up Mutt if you use a different editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:13
msgid "PREREQUISITES: None"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:16
msgid ""
"HINT: This hint will be split into two parts. The first part will be "
"configuring Vim to spell check, the other will be for Mutt alone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:19
msgid ""
"You do not need to do both, but it won't hurt if you do. You will just have "
"two different ways of spell-checking."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:21
msgid "### Setting up Vim to use Aspell ###"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:24
msgid ""
"Install aspell as per the BLFS book: "
"http://beyond.linuxfromscratch.org/view/cvs/general/aspell.html"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:26
msgid "Edit your vimrc to include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:28
msgid "map ^T :w!<CR>:!aspell check %<CR>:e! %<CR>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:31
msgid ""
"NOTE: ^T is <ctrl-t>, but in Vim you have to type <ctrl-v> to type control "
"characters. Thus you need to replace ^T with <ctrl-v><ctrl-t>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:35
msgid ""
"Once you save your vimrc, any time you are in Vim's command mode, typing "
"<ctrl-t> will cause the screen to split showing the aspell commands at the "
"bottom."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:37
msgid "If you use Vim as your editor in Mutt, you're all set to spell-check."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:39
msgid "But wait! There's more!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:46
msgid ""
"If you are replying to an email and you hit <ctrl-t> aspell will attempt to "
"spell-check the headers, signature, and all the quoted lines in addition to "
"what you actually wrote. There is a nifty little app called newsbody that "
"will allow us to copy just the body of the message to a temporary file, edit "
"it (spell-check it), then put it back into the original message, leaving "
"headers and sigs alone. It also allows us to ignore quoted lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:49
msgid ""
"You can get newsbody in a package called spellutils here: "
"http://home.worldonline.dk/byrial/spellutils/spellutils-0.7.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:54
msgid ""
"./configure && make && install -m755 newsbody /usr/bin install -m644 "
"newsbody.1 /usr/share/man/man1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:57
msgid ""
"NOTE: spellutils also builds a file pospell if you're interested in "
"spell-checking .po files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:62
msgid ""
"Now that newsbody is installed add the following lines to your vimrc: map ^R "
"\\1\\2<CR>:e! %<CR> map \\1 :w!<CR> map \\2 :!newsbody -qs -n % -p aspell "
"check \\%f<CR>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:66
msgid ""
"These lines simply let you run aspell without having to check the sig, "
"headers, or quoted text. Treat ^R the same as ^T above. You can also change "
"the letter to suit your needs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:70
msgid ""
"Now you have a way to spell-check regular documents and emails with either "
"<ctrl-t> or <ctrl-r>. You can stop here, or optionally continue on. There is "
"no added functionality below. Just a different way of doing the same thing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:72
msgid "### Setting up Mutt to use Aspell ###"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:75
msgid ""
"NOTE: I use Vim in mutt but the following should work on your editor of "
"choice as these are mutt-specific, not editor-specific."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:79
msgid ""
"The default command to spell-check in Mutt is \"i\". There are 2 ways in "
"which to invoke newsbody and aspell in mutt. We can either call a simple "
"script, or we can write a macro. I will discuss both."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:81
msgid "Script method:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:86
msgid ""
"cat >/usr/bin/spellcheck <<\"EOF\" newsbody -hqs -n $2 -p aspell check %f "
"EOF chmod 755 /usr/bin/spellcheck"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:88 origin/mutt+aspell.txt:96
msgid "add the following to your muttrc:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:90
msgid "set ispell=\"/usr/bin/spellcheck\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:92
msgid "-or-"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:94
msgid "Macro method:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/mutt+aspell.txt:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"macro compose i \\\n"
"        \"<filter-entry>newsbody -hqs -n - -p aspell check %f<enter>\" \\\n"
"        \"run aspell on the selected part\"\n"
msgstr ""

